{{distinguish|text=[[Charlton Bullseye (fanzine)]], the fanzine from the mid-1970s}} {{Refimprove|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> |title = Charlton Bullseye |image = Charlton-Bullseye01.jpg |imagesize = |caption = ''Charlton Bullseye'' #1. Art by [[Bob McLeod (comics)|Bob McLeod]] and [[Dan Reed (comics)|Dan Reed]]. |schedule = Monthly |ongoing = y |publisher = [[Charlton Comics]] |date = June [[1981 in comics|1981]] – December [[1982 in comics|1982]] |issues = 10 |writers = |artists = |pencillers = |inkers = |letterers = |colorists = |editors = |creative_team_month = |creative_team_year = |creators = |TPB = |ISBN = |subcat = |altcat = |sort = Charlton Bullseye (comics) }} '''''Charlton Bullseye''''' was the title of a short-lived [[Charlton Comics]] showcase [[comic book]] series published from June [[1981 in comics|1981]] through December [[1982 in comics|1982]]. Several new stories using Charlton's "Action Heroes" appeared, before they were sold to [[DC Comics]] in [[1983 in comics|1983]]. After the cancellation of ''Charlton Bullseye'', stories intended for the title were published in ''[[Scary Tales (comics)|Scary Tales]]'' #36–40, which explains the superhero story "Mr. Jigsaw" in issue #38 and "Dragon Force" in issue #40. Several other unpublished stories for the title were published by [[AC Comics]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Borax, Mark | date = July 1986 | title = Bill Black | journal = [[Comics Interview]] | issue = 36 | pages = 52–65 | publisher = [[Fictioneer Books]]}}</ref>
According to the 1980 press release for the series, an artist showed up at the Charlton offices and offered to work for them for free in hopes of accumulating enough credits to get a job with one of the two leading comics publishers. ''Charlton Bullseye'' was based around this concept; contributors to the series were paid only in contributor copies, all original art was returned to the artists after publication, and contributors would hold the copyrights to any original characters they introduced.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Greenberger|first=Robert|title=New Talent and Bonus Babies|journal=[[Back Issue!]]|issue=71 |page=65|publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date=April 2014|location=Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref>
==Issues== # [[Blue Beetle]] and the [[Question (comics)|Question]]. Art by [[Dan Reed (comics)|Dan Reed]]. # "Funny animal" stories, featuring the first appearance of [[Neil the Horse]], by [[Arn Saba]]. # Swords and sorcery/science fiction # The Vanguards (all-woman super team), by Larry Houston. # The Barbarian, Warhund. Art by [[Chas Truog]] and colors by Wendy Fiore. # [[E-Man|Michael Mauser]]. Story by [[Rick Burchett]]. # [[Captain Atom]], with art by [[Dan Reed (comics)|Dan Reed]]; and [[Nightshade (DC Comics)|Nightshade]], by [[Bill Black (comics)|Bill Black]]. # Horror stories # "Bludd, the Ultimate Barbarian", a science fiction barbarian story. Art partially done by [[Gene Day]]. # [[Thunder Bunny]], by [[Martin L. Greim]].
==Attempted revivals== In 1985, a final attempt at a revival was spearheaded by new editor T.C. Ford with a direct-market only version of ''Charlton Bullseye Special'', which featured work by then newcomers [[Amanda Conner]], T.C. Ford, and Chris Pridgen. United Comics, T.C. Ford's publishing house, will reprint this edition as ''Shockwave'' #1 in 2016.
