{{for|another type of farm with circular fields sometimes called "pizza farms"|central-pivot irrigation}}A '''pizza farm''' is an educational visitor attraction consisting of a small [[farm]] on a circular piece of land partitioned into plots shaped like [[pizza]] wedges. The farm's segments produce ingredients that can be used in pizza, such as [[wheat]] for the crust, [[tomato]]es or [[herb]]s, [[pork]] for [[pepperoni]], [[Dairy cattle|dairy cows]] for [[cheese]], and even trees for pizza oven [[firewood]]. Certain farms may even have access to coal or natural gas deposits that can be used as additional pizza oven heating fuels. Many of the newer pizza farms are experimenting with [[alternative energy]], such as installing [[wind turbines]] in the fields, to be more green.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}
Farms which cook their own pizzas, sometimes using ingredients grown on the farm itself, are also called "pizza farms" and have become popular in [[Minnesota]] and [[Wisconsin]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twincities.eater.com/maps/pizza-farm-minnesota-wisconsin|title=Where to Eat Pizza on a Farm|work=Eater Twin Cities|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/907652945|title=Soil sisters : a tooklit for women farmers|last=Kivirist|first=Lisa|publisher=[[New Society Publishers]]|others=|year=2016|isbn=9780865718050|location=Gabriola Island, BC|pages=135|oclc=907652945|quote=With roots originating in the Midwest, the 'pizza farm' concept involves a farm serving these cheesy tomato pies, typically with farm-raised fare as ingredients ... Pizza farms serve the pizza 'take-out' style, and guests have the option to take it home or, much more likely, bring their own gear and eat picnic-style on the farm.}}</ref>
== Examples of Pizza Farms ==
* Agriculture in the Classroom Canada has yearly student-farmed pizza farms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorktonthisweek.com/agriculture/learning-farming-via-the-pizza-1.1965002|title=Learning farming via the pizza|last=Daniels|first=Calvin|date=2015-06-10|work=Yorkton This Week|access-date=2018-10-18|archive-url=https://archive.fo/4RHqE|archive-date=2018-10-18|dead-url=no}}</ref> There are other food farms in the program, including a "burgers and fries" farm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.agcanada.com/2015/10/food-farms-are-a-hit|title=Food farms are a hit: It’s a fun way to show kids the link between farming and their burgers and pizza|last=Furber|first=Debbie|date=2015-10-23|work=AGCanada|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-US}}</ref> * The Pizza Farm at Cobb Ranch ([[Fresno, California]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepizzafarm.com:80/m-thepizzafarm.cfm|title=What's the Story? History of the Pizza Farm|last=|first=|date=|website=The Pizza Farm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206145452/http://www.thepizzafarm.com:80/m-thepizzafarm.cfm|archive-date=2008-02-06|dead-url=yes|access-date=2008-02-06}}</ref> * "R" Pizza Farm ([[Dow, Illinois]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sj-r.com/x639781489/Pizza-farm-also-a-place-to-learn-about-organic-methods|title='Pizza farm' also a place to learn about organic methods|last=Grimaldi Olsen|first=Theresa|date=2009-07-31|work=The State Journal|access-date=2018-10-18|archive-url=https://archive.fo/HqKU4|archive-date=2018-10-18|dead-url=no|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/offbeat/2005-09-15-pizza-farm_x.htm|title=Pizza-shaped farm draws tourists with organic slice|last=|first=|date=2005-09-15|website=[[USAToday]].com|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://archive.fo/D4ZF4|archive-date=2018-10-18|dead-url=no|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref>
