[[File:SQF catching.jpg|300px|thumbnail|right|This squirrel is just about to catch the peanut.]] [[Image:Squirrel-lift.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A squirrel being successfully lifted]] '''Squirrel fishing''' is the sporting practice of "catching" [[squirrel]]s and attempting to lift them into the air using a nut (preferably a [[peanut]]) tied to a string or [[fishing line]], and optionally some kind of [[fishing pole]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://media.www.dailyemerald.com/media/storage/paper859/news/2004/05/05/Commentary/A.Noble.Line.Reel.Squirrel.Fishing.In.As.Club.Sport-1970277.shtml?sourcedomain=www.dailyemerald.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |title=Commentary: A noble line: Reel squirrel fishing in as Club sport |newspaper=Oregon Daily Emerald |date=May 5, 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124153510/http://media.www.dailyemerald.com/media/storage/paper859/news/2004/05/05/Commentary/A.Noble.Line.Reel.Squirrel.Fishing.In.As.Club.Sport-1970277.shtml?sourcedomain=www.dailyemerald.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |archivedate=November 24, 2007}}</ref>
There has been some debate over where modern squirrel fishing originated. The practice was popularized by Nicholas Middleton and Zmira Zilkha during their summers at [[Middlebury College]] Italian Language School, by Nikolas Gloy and Yasuhiro Endo at the Division of Engineering and Applied Sciences at [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Techtv: Leo Laportes 2003 Technology Almanac|first=Leo|title=Techtv: Leo Laportes 2003 Technology Almanac|publisher=Pearson Education|year=2006|pages=34|isbn=978-0-7897-2847-0}}</ref> and by the Berkeley Squirrel Fisher's Club (BSF), an official student group at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], that has been featured in the campus newspaper.<ref>{{cite news |first=Bryan |last=Ritchie |url=http://archive.dailycal.org/article.php?id=8598 |title=Nutty Goodness |newspaper=The Daily Californian |date=May 6, 2002 }}</ref> {{As of|2009}}, [[Ohio State University]] also had a squirrel fishing club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legal.osu.edu/media/PowePointpresentationsfromRepresentingOSU%2800059299%29.PDF |title=Representing OSU: A Conference for Legal Counsel, November 20, 2009 |accessdate=December 12, 2014 |format=pdf |page=8 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Michigan State University]] was late to join in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theblacksheeponline.com/campus-life/msus-newest-sport-squirrel-fishing |title=MSU’s Newest Sport: Squirrel Fishing |accessdate=December 11, 2017 |format=html }}</ref>
Squirrel fishing occurred at least as early as 1889 in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88085488/1889-04-06/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1836&index=1&rows=20&words=fishing+Squirrel&searchType=basic&sequence=0&state=&date2=1922&proxtext=squirrel+fishing&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 |newspaper=The Pullman Herald|title=The Pacific Coast |date=April 6, 1889 |page=1 }}</ref> == References == {{Reflist}}
